{"ts":"2026-06-27T11:16:36.090Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Examining API Route Structure**\n\nI'm now diving deeper into Next.js API route structure. It appears these are TypeScript-based and use named exports for HTTP methods. I'm focusing on the standard format, especially the `export async function POST(req: Request)` syntax. Moving on to the design plan to gain more context.\n\n\n**Adapting Design Plan for API**\n\nI'm adapting the design plan to the API context, questioning its initial applicability. The \"Page or section narrative\" translates to the security function of these endpoints. It's becoming apparent that principles like a \"Visual metaphor\" can represent secure endpoint design. I'm focusing on JWT validation and structured JSON responses to meet enterprise-grade endpoint goals.\n\n\n**Refining Secure Endpoint Design**\n\nI'm now viewing the design through the lens of cryptographic enclaves and robust handshakes. The \"visual\" is becoming apparent: it's the structure of the JSON responses and headers. I'm focusing on a RESTful layout with standardized Next.js App Router endpoints, ensuring consistent success/error JSON responses, and leaning towards using a secure JWT library in TypeScript for signing. Finally, I'm streamlining the interaction strategy to a clean request-response pattern and clear HTTP status codes.\nI'm ensuring precise JSON payload checks, too, and robust token verification.\nMobile clients will receive standard, optimized JSON responses. I'm creating several files: `app/api/v1/auth/login/route.ts` and `app/api/v1/auth/me/route.ts` and I'll include the necessary security in the structure, too.\n\n\n**Analyzing New Files and Constraints**\n\nI've created `app/api/v1/auth/logout/route.ts` and `lib/api-auth.ts`, a JWT helper. I'm carefully avoiding modifications to the landing page and tool files as instructed. The current focus is on understanding user data. The login API needs to verify email/password and return a JWT. \"Me\" requires a bearer token, and \"Logout\" is just token discard. Now, I'm checking the admin page for user examples.\n\n\n**Defining User Access Security**\n\nI'm now considering the mock user passwords to finalize the login endpoint. I'm choosing to define secure, unique, mock passwords for each user, prioritizing realistic enterprise security standards. I'm focusing on user email validation, password verification, JWT generation, and returning the user info. Finally, I'll review and ensure the login endpoint returns the JWT access token and user information.\n\n\n**Implementing User Account Status**\n\nI'm now incorporating account status handling, specifically for inactive users. The mock database will now include an `inactive` user. Login endpoint design now incorporates error messages for inactive users. I'm verifying inactive account errors and also designing mock databases. I'm prioritizing error handling within API, also. I have user data, and I'll include user roles in the response.\n\n\n"}}
